{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656981"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.03,0.72,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27866"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a three-month history of epigastric pain. The pain is burning in nature, worse before meals, and improves with eating. She has occasional nausea but no vomiting. She denies use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. Her medical history do not contain anything of note.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her abdomen is soft with mild epigastric tenderness. Upper endoscopy is performed and a view of the first part of the duodenum is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this ulcer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenocarcinoma","Crohn disease","Cytomegalovirus infection","Helicobacter pylori infection","Zollinger-Ellison syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms of peptic ulcer disease, including epigastric pain that improves with meals. Given the absence of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug use or other risk factors, \u003Cstrong\u003EHelicobacter pylori infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause. \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection is responsible for approximately 80% of duodenal ulcers in patients not taking non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause duodenal ulceration, but this typically presents with other gastrointestinal symptoms, and the ulcers are often multiple and may occur throughout the gastrointestinal tract. There are no extra-intestinal manifestations or other features suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZollinger-Ellison syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by gastrinoma causing excessive acid production, typically presents with multiple or refractory ulcers, severe symptoms, and may be associated with diarrhoea. It is rare and usually associated with multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E causing peptic ulceration is primarily seen in immunocompromised patients. This patient has no history suggesting immunocompromise, making this an unlikely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the duodenum is very uncommon. If the underlying cause was malignancy, it is most likely that there would have been other symptoms such as anorexia and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient should include testing for \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection (if not already done) and appropriate eradication therapy if positive, along with proton pump inhibitor therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Helicobacter pylori infection and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs are the two most common causes of peptic ulcer disease.","A detailed medication history is essential in evaluating patients with peptic ulcer disease.","Zollinger-Ellison syndrome should be considered in patients with refractory or multiple peptic ulcers."],"references":["Vakil, N. Peptic Ulcer Disease: A Review, JAMA, 2024, https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39466269/#:~:text=The%20principal%20causes%20of%20peptic,people%20with%20peptic%20ulcer%20disease."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21483"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21483"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/q2DKN2qvM2KC6cNJHkW8Rex55DKMe2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/q2DKN2qvM2KC6cNJHkW8Rex55DKMe2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":705,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T09:43:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T09:45:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11790"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","